[asy]
pair A,B,C;
A=(0,0);
B=(1,0);
C=(1,1);
draw(A--C--B--cycle);
draw(rightanglemark(A,B,C,2));
label("$45^\circ$",A,SW);
label("$60^\circ$",B,SE);
label("$h$",(1.2,0.5));
label("$d$",(0.5,-0.2));
label("$x$",(0.5,0.5));
[/asy]

Using the tangent function, we have $\tan 45^\circ = \frac{h}{x}$ and $\tan 60^\circ = \frac{h}{x+d}$. Simplifying these equations gives us $x=h$ and $x+d=\sqrt{3}h$. Solving this system of equations gives us $d=\sqrt{3}h-h=(\sqrt{3}-1)h$.

Since the car is traveling at a uniform speed, the ratio of the distance traveled to the time taken is constant. Therefore, the ratio of $d$ to the time taken for the angle of elevation to change from $45^\circ$ to $60^\circ$ is equal to the ratio of $d$ to the time it takes for the car to reach the base of the tower. The time taken for the angle of elevation to change from $45^\circ$ to $60^\circ$ is $10$ minutes, so we have $\frac{d}{10}=\frac{d}{t}$. Solving for $t$ gives us $t=10$ minutes.

Therefore, the car will take $\boxed{\textbf{(E) None of these}}$ more time to reach the base of the tower.'

